Formalization of the main theorem from the Quench paper.
We define the DKPS nearest-neighbor predictor and the baseline subset-score predictor.
We prove that under the DKPS concentration hypothesis and a denseness assumption on the model distribution,
the MSE of the DKPS predictor converges to 0 in probability as the number of reference models and responses increases.
Consequently, if the baseline predictor has strictly positive MSE, the DKPS predictor eventually achieves strictly lower MSE with high probability, establishing query efficiency.
-/



